chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Abortion law should start from two shared priorities: protecting patients’ health and safety through evidence-based care, and treating developing life with moral seriousness without imposing one religious or ideological view on everyone. A balanced framework keeps early, time-sensitive decisions primarily with the patient and qualified clinicians, while drawing any later-pregnancy restrictions in clear, medically workable terms and always preserving prompt exceptions for life and serious health risks, rape or incest, and lethal or profoundly nonviable fetal conditions. To reduce conflict and the number of crisis pregnancies, government should invest at least as much in prevention and support—contraception, medically accurate education, prenatal/postpartum care, and concrete parenting or adoption resources—so choices are less driven by fear, poverty, or lack of options.
